<h2>Overview</h2>
<p>
    The application simplifies company search experience making it more relevant. It distinguishes "what", "where" and "how" to search.
    It remembers user search history to build advisory profile, communicates with other systems and searching engines without duplicating content.
    It minimises navigation efforts, hides complexity and visualizes search results summary.<br />
</p>
<h2>Getting started</h2>
<p>
    If you put your search term - or parts of it - in quotes, you’ll get more specific results. For instance, “mark hamill” “star wars” would probably get better results than mark hamill star wars.
    Your search term should sound like the answer you’re looking for rather than the question. So search for “2015 academy award winner” instead of “who was that guy who won that film award in 2015”?
    Be LESS specific. Every new word you add is narrowing your results!
    Additionally, we use domain specific language to help with search creteries.
    If you want to search within a single folder, try “mysearch {Scope:\\shared_folred_path}”.
    Use “mysearch {Modified:This Year} ” to find files last modified this year.
</p>
